Enclosed is a modified version of DOMConfigurator.java, based on the current CVS version 1.27.  This modified version supports java.io.Reader objects in the method doConfigure(), instead of only InputStream. org.xml.sax.InputSource supports a constructor which takes a Reader object, so the change is very simple:- modified the existing doConfigure(InputStream, Hierarchy) method tondoConfigure(InputSource, Hierarchy) and made it protected instead of public.n- created a new public version of doConfigure(InputStream,Hierarchy) whichncalls doConfigure(InputSource, Hierarchy).n- created a new public method, doConfigure(Reader, Hierarchy), which callsndoConfigure(InputSource, Hierarchy).nnnThat's it.  I needed this modification because I have a case where the xmlnconfiguration data is coming from a string, not a file.  So I need to usenthe java.io.StringReader class to wrap the existing string.nnnnPR:nObtained from:nSubmitted by: Mark WomacknReviewed by: Celonnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@309271 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n

Added ZeroConf support to most of the network-based appenders and receivers.To enable ZeroConf advertising of an appender or receiver, a user can now:n - add jmdns jar to their classpath n - set the 'advertiseViaMulticastDNS' param to 'true'nnAlso added support for discovery of appenders in Chainsaw (Chainsaw will automatically configure a matching receiver when connected).nSupported appenders:nSocketAppendernSocketHubAppender (ZeroConfSocketHubAppender is still functional)nUDPAppendernMulticastAppendernSupported receivers:nSocketReceivernSocketHubReceiver (also receives events from ZeroConfSocketHubAppender)nXMLSocketReceiver (can receive events sent over TCP by other logging frameworks)nUDPReceivernMulticastReceivernnImplementation details:n - removed Zeroconf4log4j class, jmdns access is now through the ZeroConfSupport class (class provides support of JmDNS and ServiceInfo creation via reflection, and supports both jmdns 1.0 and jmdns 3.1 apis)n - ZeroConfSupport class is now used by ZeroConfSocketHubAppender, Chainsaw and all appenders & receivers that can advertise their configuration via ZeroConfn - added new 'advertiseViaMulticastDNS' param to the appenders and receivers that support ZeroConfn - updated the ZeroConf site documentationn - updated release notesn - updated the ZeroConfPlugin html filen - tested appenders with 1.0 and 3.1 jmdns jarsn - updated log4j references in poms to log4j 1.2.16-snapshot where necessary nnFor those wanting to add ZeroConf support to third-party appenders and have Chainsaw discover the appenders, the service info naming convention is described here: https://issues.apache.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=48907nnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@924176 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n

Cosmetic changes. Changes javac to use target attribute of 1.1.  Per the Ant documentation: Generate class files for specific VM version (e.g., 1.1 or 1.2). Note that the default value depends on the JVM that is running Ant. In particular, if you use JDK 1.4+ the generated classes will not be usable for a 1.1 Java VM unless you explicitly set this attribute to the value 1.1 (which is the default value for JDK 1.1 to 1.3). Added a new filter which expects JavaBeans-style objects passed in the logger.debug, etc. calls as the message. This fixes an NPE that can occur.Stephen Pain noticed that when a Receiver is restarted in Chainsaw, the GUI looks fine, but no events are displayednfrom that point onwards.  A real bummer.nnIt turns out that it is during the restart of Socket based Receivers, an LoggingEvent is sent throughndescribing the socket close issue.  Unfortunately the event has no properties set.nnCurrently the LoggingEvent.getProperties() method could return null. Bug fix commit Changes:* build.xml - copy logger.dtd into jarn* locationinfo - non-log4j apps may only specify a subset of the locationinfo fields (the rest would be null), a check was added to prevent an NPE on each accessorn* loggingevent - Added locationInformationExists method (getLocationInfo creates a location info if it does not exist), and added exist checks to code as needed to prevent location info constructionn* loggingevent - modified setProperty behavior, if value is null, the property is removedn* receiverpanel - add xmlsocketreceiver support(built-in support for reception of xml-formatted log4j events via tcp socket)n* utillogginglevel - modified intvalues so that the lowest value is greater than log4j's debug level intvalue (so the appender skeleton would forward the events correctly with threshold set to debug)n* fileloadaction - when attempting to load an xml file, directories are displayed as well as xml filesn* modified thread code in chainsawappenderhandler in an attempt to improve performancen* multicastappender/udpappender - removing internally specified properties (log4japp/log4jmachine name) so the rest of the appenders in the appender chain could specify these properties themselves or the default behavior of using the remote machine could be usedn* multicastappender/receiver, udpappender/receiver added encoding support (chartset) as a property.  If none set, the default system encoding is used.n* xmlsocketreceiver/udpreceiver/multicastreceiver - added pausable support (useful in receiver panel)nnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@310152 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n

This is quite a massive commit. Here is a short summary:- The o.a.l.helpers.PatternParser class has been moved ton o.a.l.pattern package. nnMany of the small PatternConverter classes contained in nPatternParser.java  file have been taken out  and placed in no.a.l.pattern package as  independent class files.nnThe Layout class has changed. A new method nn  void format(Writer output, LoggingEvent event)nnhas been added. Instead of returning a String, Layouts now write ndirectly to the output stream. This significantly improves performance, nin particular by avoiding the  creation of many temporary strings.nnThe  method nn  String  format(LoggingEvent event) nnin Layout is kept around for compatibility. This method is now nimplemented in terms of the format(Writer, LoggingEvent) variant nwhere Writer is a CharArrayWriter.nnThe changes pass the existing unit tests.nnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@309848 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n

Patch from Raymond DeCampo:Chainsaw is now capable of remembering the size and position of the mainnwindow, the position of the table/details divider, the width and ordernof all the columns, whether or not each column is displayed, the statenof the filtes and a recent files list.  The number of files in thenrecent files list is configurable, as is the whether the state of thenfilters is preserved.  These preferences are accessible from thenFile->Preferences menu option.  The preference dialog also allows thenuser to select which columns are shown.  Mnemonic shortcuts have beennadded to all menu items.  The recent files submenu is under the Filenmenu.  The preferences are stored under the user's home directorey byndefault but the preference file and any individual preference may benoverridden by the system properties.  Chainsaw will handle the absencenof the preferences file by creating it; no errors should arise from anynpreference not being defined.nnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@309754 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n

Search for resource using the thread context class loader under Java2. If that fails, search for resource using the class loader that loaded this class (Loader). Under JDK 1.1, only the the class loader that loaded this class (Loader) is used.Try one last time with ClassLoader.getSystemResource(resource),nthat is is using the system class loader in JDK 1.2 and virtualnmachine's built-in class loader in JDK 1.1.nnThe difference with the previous code was that under Java2, thenclassloader of org.apache.log4j.helpers.Loader was *not* tried if thenthread context loader was set. However, this is incorrect logic becasenThread.getContextClassLoader always returns a value.nnThread.getContextClassLoader javadoc reads:nn Returns the context ClassLoader for this Thread. The contextn ClassLoader is provided by the creator of the thread for use by coden running in this thread when loading classes and resources. If not set,n the default is the ClassLoader context of the parent Thread. Then context ClassLoader of the primordial thread is typically set to then class loader used to load the application.nnIf an application server chooses not to set the thread context classnloader, then Thread.getContextClassLoader returns the classpathnclassloader which usually not what is desired.nnnPR:nObtained from:nSubmitted by:nReviewed by:nnngit-svn-id: https://svn.apache.org/repos/asf/logging/log4j/trunk@309345 13f79535-47bb-0310-9956-ffa450edef68n
